passages.text: Earnings review: 1H25A below expectation; depressed poultry margin; Maintain Neutral
300498.SZ 12m Price Target: Rmb19.00 Price: Rmb18.19 Upside: \(4.5\%\)

Wens reported 1H25A net profit of Rmb3.47bn, or EPS of Rmb0.522/sh, versus Rmb1.34bn in 1H24A. Excluding one- off items mainly on inventory impairment loss for yellow- feather broiler, fair value gain and non- operating costs, recurring NP was Rmb3.67bn, versus Rmb1.28bn a year ago. The results were below our expectation and likely behind Refinitiv consensus, due to depressed yellow- feather poultry margin. Wens declared no interim dividend, same as last year.

We revise recurring earnings estimates for Wens by - 32% in 2025E, \(+8\%\) in 2026E, and \(+6\%\) in 2027E, to incorporate higher hog profit, partly offset by lower poultry margin. We expect improving supply/demand fundamentals in China domestic hog market for 2026E, driven by potential improving industry supply discipline, related to control in sow herd, output weight and secondary fattening, amid demand likely to remain soft. Wen's increasing effort in cost cutting, through breeding development, more effective disease control, and optimizing feed formulation, is also expected to support unit profit in hog operations in 2026E. While yellow- feather broiler margin is depressed, we expect improvements in 2026E, as supply response from farmers emerges based on producer's feedback. Current share price implies 11x P/E on 2026E, versus its historical range of 10- 20x, fair in our view. Maintain Neutral with a revised 12- m target price of Rmb19.0/sh (from Rmb17.0/sh).

For hog production, we lowered gross profit by \(29\%\) in 2H25E, to factor in soften pricing in 3Q25A. We maintain our improving hog pricing outlook for domestic market, at Rmb16.5/kg in 2026E, driven by supply discipline, versus Rmb14.7/kg in 1H25A. We also lower total unit cost assumption by \(5\%\) in 2H25E, and \(4\%\) by 2026E, factoring higher FCR, and lower unit piglet cost on higher PSY, to drive up sector gross profit by \(8\%\) in 2026E, versus prior estimate. We expect Wens to benefit from its increasing focus on breeding technology, through established breeding platform, and introduction of high- quality breeding hogs.

For poultry production, we lowered gross profit by \(48\%\) in 2H25E, mostly incorporating lower benchmark yellow- feather broiler pricing at Rmb12.3/kg, \(8\%\) lower than prior. However, we expected pricing improved to Rmb12.7/kg in 2026E, as result of improving supply discipline, partly offsetting downside risk from excess capacity in breeding broiler (grand- parent generation).

Hog (95% of total gross profit): Gross profit was inline with expectation, up \(125\%\) yoy, driven by lower unit production cost and higher sales volume. Total unit cost of market hog was lowered to Rmb12.5/kg in 1H25A, Rmb1.9/kg lower yoy, mostly driven by improvement in key performance ratios, including Rmb0.7/kg from lower unit piglet cost, Rmb0.1/kg from higher FCR, and Rmb0.8/kg from lower feed purchase price. Sales volume of market hog was 17.9mn head, \(25\%\) higher yoy, outperforming the national market of \(1\%\) , inline with expectation. By end of 1H25A, total sow herd size was 1.85mnt head, \(6\%\) higher versus end of 2024A.

Yellow- feather broiler (1% of total gross profit): Gross profit was below our expectation, amid depressed poultry pricing, partly offset by lower unit production cost. During 1H25A, realized ASP of yellow- feather broilers (incl. processing) was \(17\%\) lower yoy, due to soft demand, with price premium narrowed to \(4\%\) , from \(7\%\) in 1H24A versus domestic benchmark price. Total unit improved by \(8\%\) yoy, or Rmb1.1/kg, mostly driven by lower unit feed cost (Rmb0.7/kg). Sales volume was \(9\%\) higher yoy, outperforming
the industry, driven by penetration in fresh and package chicken production, above our expectation.

Operation costs and others: Total SG&A was better than expected, due to lower employee incentive cost recognized during the period. Wens also reported impairment loss of Rmb522mn, for its inventory on yellow- feather broiler.
Cash flow: Operating cash flow was \(11\%\) higher yoy, inline with profit trend. FCF was Rmb1.7bn in 1H25A, versus Rmb1.6bn a year ago. CAPEX was Rmb4.7bn in 1H25A, mostly on maintenance.
Balance sheet and gearing: Net debt was Rmb11.3bn as of end of 1H25A, with net gearing at \(25\%\) , versus \(24\%\) at the end of 2024A.

Our valuation is based on an average of Wens' near- term and long- term valuations. Specifically, we use Wens' past 12- m market P/E of 10x to derive our near- term valuation, while our long- term valuation is based on SOTP, including 10x P/E on the hog business and 10x on poultry business, rolling forward to 2030E, using a discount rate of \(10\%\) back to 2026E (rolling from 2025E). Our new target price implies a P/E of 17x for 2025E, and 8x for 2026E.

Key risks include: (1) Uncertainties in hog prices, which are mostly affected by industry supply changes including both domestic supply and imports, especially the production of oversized hogs which we believe have intrinsically changed the hog cycle in China; (2) Execution risk in new project expansion, which could be affected by breeding herd management and other project- related drivers. (3) Operational risks centered around bio- security measures and disease control, and environmental risk, especially for Wens whose projects are mostly located in southern China. (4)
Stronger/Weaker- than- expected chicken prices and volumes, which can be affected by improved/softer industry S/D coming from excess capacity or changes in protein consumption preferences.

Wens is one of the largest hog farming companies in China, and also ranks first in China's yellow- feather farming industry, with 30.2mn heads of hog output and 1.2bn feathers of chicken sales in 2024A. We expect improving supply/demand fundamentals in China domestic hog market for 2026E, driven by potential improving industry supply discipline, related to control in sow herd, output weight and secondary fattening, amid demand likely to remain soft. Wen's increasing effort in cost cutting, through breeding development, more effective disease control, and optimizing feed formulation, is also expected to support unit profit in hog operation in 2026E. While yellow- feather broiler margin is depressed, we expect improvements in 2026E, as supply response from farmers emerges based on producer's feedback. We are Neutral rated on Wens as we believe its current valuation fairly reflected its earning growth outlook in poultry and hog segment.

Key risks include: (1) Uncertainties in hog prices, which are mostly affected by industry supply changes including both domestic supply and imports, especially the production of oversized hogs which we believe have intrinsically changed the hog cycle in China; (2) Faster/slower- than- expected capacity expansion of hog farming, which could be affected by breeding herd management and other project- related drivers. (3) Better/worse- than- expected cost control in hog farming centered around bio- security measures and disease control, could lead to higher/lower unit profit; (4) Stronger/Weaker- than- expected chicken prices and volumes, which can be affected by improved/softer industry S/D coming from excess capacity or changes in protein
consumption preferences.

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.
